<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="63" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[140,1108,1152,1672]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,310,1398,1424]" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis box="[185,304,1398,1424]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
This species can be most readily recognized for the black to dark brown coloration and the basal area of the propodeum lacking distinct striae reaching to the apical margin. For those species in which males are known the structure of the exposed (
<emphasis box="[149,249,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="63">vide infra</emphasis>
) and hidden sterna (Figs 4–5), as well as the genitalia (Figs 6–7) are diagnostic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
